			<ns0:name>mseaborn@chromium.org</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/mseaborn@chromium.org/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">The untrusted-code Gyp build does not handle incremental builds correctly: it misses header file dependencies.

I found that if I change nacl_srpc.h, &amp;quot;make chrome&amp;quot; does not rebuild the IRT.

When I look in the Gyp-generated srpc_lib.target.mk, &amp;quot;nacl_srpc.h&amp;quot; is not listed.  The scan_sources.py invocation has not returned nacl_srpc.h.

I think scan_sources.py is being invoked incorrectly.  Gyp runs it from src/shared/srpc, but it's run with the arguments &amp;quot;-I.&amp;quot; and &amp;quot;-I..&amp;quot; -- the wrong include path.  There seems to be an assumption that scan_sources.py is run from the &amp;quot;native_client&amp;quot; directory or Chromium's &amp;quot;src&amp;quot; directory.

This is blocking an update of NaCl's revision in Chromium's DEPS:  Roland's cleanup change (http://src.chromium.org/viewvc/native_client?view=rev&amp;amp;revision=7401) does not get rebuilt properly.  Different parts of the IRT get different layouts of &amp;quot;struct NaClSrpcChannel&amp;quot; which causes a check to fail at run time.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2012-02-29T21:19:20.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2011-12-17T01:28:01.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:status>Started</ns2:status><ns2:owner>
